"Chen K., McAneney J., Cheung K.","Quantifying changes of wind speed distributions in the historical record of Atlantic tropical cyclones",2009,"Natural Hazards and Earth System Science","9","5",,"1749","1757",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71749092662&partnerID=40&md5=b2c1a868331b0c0dbeb9a403a5a7fcfc","Risk Frontiers Natural Hazards Research Centre, Macquarie University, NSW, 2109, Australia; Department of Environment and Geography, Macquarie University, NSW, 2109, Australia","Chen, K., Risk Frontiers Natural Hazards Research Centre, Macquarie University, NSW, 2109, Australia; McAneney, J., Risk Frontiers Natural Hazards Research Centre, Macquarie University, NSW, 2109, Australia; Cheung, K., Department of Environment and Geography, Macquarie University, NSW, 2109, Australia","Here we re-examine the official Atlantic basin tropical cyclone (hurricane) database HURDAT (1851ĝ€""2008) and quantify differences between wind speed distributions in the early historical (1851ĝ€""1943) record and more recent observations. Analyses were performed at three different geographical levels: for all six-hourly track segments of all Atlantic basin events, all segments of all events that crossed the US mainland, and US landfalling segments alone. At all three geographical levels of study, distributions of windspeeds over the last two, four and six decades display negligible dispersion or systematic change over time. On the other hand and relative to wind speed frequencies for subsequent years, the 1851ĝ€""1943 record has a marked and statistically significant over-representation of wind speeds largely corresponding to Saffir-Simpson Categories 1 and 2 and under-representation of Categories 4 and 5 events; importantly, no single Category 5 event is recorded prior to 1924. The stability of the distribution of windspeeds at landfall over the last six decades, the dataset in which we can have most confidence, suggests that the differences in the earlier record are most likely explained by well-known measurement and observational deficiencies. Moreover by disaggregating the Power Dissipation Index (PDI), we demonstrate that the upward trend in Atlantic basin PDI since 1970s does not imply stronger and longer duration Category 5 windspeeds despite a warming climate. These results have implications for hurricane catastrophe loss modeling for the insurance industry and long-term trend analyses of the historical wind speed record, especially those related to the attribution of the role of Global Climate Change.",,"climate change; climate modeling; confidence interval; data set; database; frequency analysis; observational method; quantitative analysis; spatial distribution; storm track; temporal variation; trend analysis; tropical cyclone; wind direction; wind velocity; Atlantic Ocean; North America; United States",,,,,,"Blake, E.S., Rappaport, E.N., Landsea, C.W., The Deadliest, costliest, and most intense united states tropical cyclones from 1851 to 2006 (and other frequently requested hurricane facts) (2007) NOAA Technical Memorandum NWS TPC-5, , National Hurricane Center, Miami, Florida; Chang, E.K.M., Guo, Y., Is the number of North Atlantic tropical cyclones significantly underestimated prior to the availability of satellite observations? (2007) Geophysical Research Letters, 34 (14), pp. L14801. , DOI 10.1029/2007GL030169; Chenoweth, M., Divine, D., A document-based 318- year record of tropical cyclones in the lesser antilles, 1690 - 2007 (2008) Geochem. Geophy. Geosy., 9, pp. Q08013. , doi:10.1029/2008GC002066; Crompton, R.P., McAneney, K.J., Normalised Australian insured losses from meteorological hazards: 1967-2006 (2008) Environ. Sci. Policy, 11, pp. 371-378; Emanuel, K., Sundararajan, R., Williams, J., Hurricanes and global warming: Results from downscaling IPCC AR4 simulations (2008) B. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 89, pp. 347-367; Emanuel, K., Environmental factors affecting tropical cyclone power dissipation (2007) J. Climat